This has nothing to do with the `--unstable` flag.  When you supply a `"lib"` setting in TypeScript, it discards all the built in libraries.  Your `deno.jsonc` needs to be more like this:

```jsonc
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "lib": [
      "dom",
      "dom.iterable",
      "dom.asynciterable",
      "deno.ns",
      "deno.unstable"
    ]
  }
}
```

In addition, you are using https://deno.land/x/twd@v0.4.8/mod.ts which has:

```ts
/// <reference no-default-lib="true"/>
/// <reference lib="deno.ns" />
/// <reference lib="dom" />
/// <reference lib="esnext" />
```

Which is resetting the libs you are providing.  I forked your [gist](https://gist.github.com/kitsonk/b75a862f0795e09363d4f230c02b48b5) and added the following to the top of your `bundle.ts`:

```ts
/// <reference no-default-lib="true"/>
/// <reference lib="deno.ns" />
/// <reference lib="deno.unstable" />
/// <reference lib="dom" />
/// <reference lib="dom.iterable" />
/// <reference lib="dom.asynciterable" />
```

And it now works when you run it:

```
> deno run --unstable -A https://gist.githubusercontent.com/kitsonk/b75a862f0795e09363d4f230c02b48b5/raw/809983b272b17e9a74414d1c62c9f7be59679241/bundler.ts 
```

@kt3k your libs in `twd` are incomplete and as you can see, that way of providing the configuration can cause breakage unless it is overridden further up the stack.  I think you might want to consider not using the triple-slash references and inform people that they will need to provide a configuration providing the proper libraries.  The triple-slash references are a big hammer.

@creepinson you can see an example of integrating oak, unstable APIs and twind here: https://github.com/denoland/docland, which does not require the triple-slash references.

I would say this, FFI security fall under module integrity security, Deno currently provide an integrity checksum by running ```deno cache --lock=lock.json --lock-write mod.ts```.

So, if we could get Deno to also enforce this for FFI, we can call it a day and say Deno load only secure modules.

Assuming an attacker can edit files but not the ```lock.json``` file, then any attack that edit files will not work, meaning you are responsible to only use secure FFI.

For your first point, my understanding is this, if I know that an FFI export named "readSettings" reads a file, it is feasible to think about use the same permission model on FFI, like this:

```ts
const library = Deno.dlopen("./lib.so", {
  readSettings: {
    // this api does not exits yet
    readPermission: true // deno throw whitout --allow-read
  },
});
```

This will introduce more ambiguity though, because now if an export is not marked with this kind of permission flag I could assume it is safe to use.

On a final note, only function that are executed by the Deno process itself can be considered ```"secure"``` as long as the process is not altered and does not contain bug or exploits, which is a guarantee that Deno does not claim in the first place.

