If you have control over the server that hosts the scripts, you can include the cache bust pattern in the pathname itself.
So for instance:
```js
await import(`http://localhost:8080/${Date.now()}/myRemoteModule.ts`);
```

And then on the server[^1]:
```ts
import { route, type Route } from "@std/http/unstable-route";
import { serveDir } from "@std/http/file_server";

const routes: Route[] = [
  {
    pattern: new URLPattern({ pathname: "/:cacheBust/*" }),
    handler: (req, _info, params) => {
      serveDir(req, {
        urlRoot: `/${params?.pathname.groups.cacheBust}/`
      }),
    },
  },
];

function defaultHandler(_req: Request) {
  return new Response("Not found", { status: 404 });
}

Deno.serve(route(routes, defaultHandler));
```

This basically allows any string to be prepended to the path, causing any referenced dependencies to inherit the same cache bust value as the parent. As long as the imports are all relative anyway.

