I have dug through the code and it looks like the issue is that we are falsely making the assumption that having a type parameter extend another type with default generic values would make TypeScript automatically infer the values of the generic values.  However, it eagerly computes the type using the default generic values.  For example:

```ts
type Person<Name extends string = "John", Age extends number = 23> = { name: Name; age: Age };

// the type param is actually saying `P extends { name: "John"; age: 23 }`
type DisplayPerson<P extends Person> = `${P["name"]} is ${P["age"]} year${P["age"] extends 1 ? "" : "s"} old`;

// and the error proves this

type a = DisplayPerson<{ name: "Hey"; age: 5 }>;
// Type '{ name: "Hey"; age: 5; }' does not satisfy the constraint 'Person<"John", 23>'.
//  Types of property 'name' are incompatible.
//    Type '"Hey"' is not assignable to type '"John"'. (ts-2344)
```

I'd assume the TypeScript checker is just running into this error in a conditional and tries to just battle on in which we seem to just end up with `never`.

Here are some instances where this is incorrectly done:

1. `UnsafeCallback`
    - Def https://github.com/denoland/deno/blob/main/cli/dts/lib.deno.unstable.d.ts#L543
    - Usage https://github.com/denoland/deno/blob/main/cli/dts/lib.deno.unstable.d.ts#L559
2. `ForeignLibraryInterface`: this is the big one which basically just bubbles up and breaks all of the types
   - https://github.com/denoland/deno/blob/main/cli/dts/lib.deno.unstable.d.ts#L430

Also, I think this or something around it is probably what caused the change / break: https://github.com/denoland/deno/blob/main/cli/dts/lib.deno.unstable.d.ts#L433-L437

Here's the previous types: https://github.com/denoland/deno/blob/21dfeea3c48cf6101d71b39a1d2b0f9406818300/cli/dts/lib.deno.unstable.d.ts#L397-L413

The `StaticForeignFunctionParameters` does not offer a `never` option, so I think that here even though the type parameter given doesn't fit the definition of `ForeignFunction`, some sort of type inference happens anyway. Note that the `ForeignLibraryInterface` you linked to as the big one was not changed in the PR, and neither was any of the types "above" it. As such, I don't see how it could be the root cause.

So why would the type parameter given `StaticForeignFunctionParameters` fit the definition of `ForeignFunction`? It's because the types expects readonly arrays. So in eg.
```ts
const lib = Deno.dlopen(path, {
    add: {
        parameters: ['isize', 'isize'],
        result: 'isize'
    }
});
```
the `parameters` array is not readonly, from TS perspective it's okay to push and pop from it. As such, for TS it's an `"isize"[]` array and not an `["isize", "isize"]`.

Now, contrast this typing with the new parameters inference: https://github.com/denoland/deno/blob/main/cli/dts/lib.deno.unstable.d.ts#L379-L385
If the parameters array is readonly empty, then return an empty array. If the parameters array is a readonly array with one or more items, return the mapped type plus mapped rest. Otherwise, return `never`. I think this added `never` branch compared to the previous types is what you're seeing.

