I think this is actually two different but related issues:

- `waitAsync` isn't an async op, and V8 doesn't count it as a pending background task (in [`v8::Isolate::has_pending_background_tasks`](https://docs.rs/v8/latest/v8/struct.Isolate.html#method.has_pending_background_tasks)), so therefore it doesn't count as something that can keep the event loop alive. It's effectively unref'd.
- `waitAsync`, along with GC, `WeakRef`/`FinalizationRegistry` callbacks and WebAssembly async compilation, are things that happen when the V8 message loop is drained. V8 usually expects the message loop to be more or less continuously drained, so that the message loop _is_ the event loop, but Deno instead drains the message loop at the beginning of every event loop iteration. As such, V8 doesn't have any way to wake up Deno's event loop, and the `waitAsync` timeout will only fire when the event loop is woken up in some other way:

  ```js
  setTimeout(() => console.log("timeout", new Date()), 5000);

  const sab = new SharedArrayBuffer(4);
  const int32 = new Int32Array(sab);
  Atomics.waitAsync(int32, 0, 0, 50).value.then(() => console.log("waitAsync", new Date()));

  console.log(new Date());
  ```

Async function outlives the function scope so Rust will correctly prevent you from using it in the async block. One way to do this safely is to use hybrid ops:
```rust
#[op(v8)]
fn op_my_op(
  scope: &mut v8::HandleScope,
  a: serde_v8::Value,
) -> Result<impl Future<Output = Result<T, AnyError>> + 'static, AnyError> {
   // You can use the HandleScope here.
   // Ideally, create owned Rust values to pass into the async block below.
   let i: i32 = a.v8_value.int32_value(scope);
   Ok(async move {
      // .. 
   })
}
```

