> Why not using `core.tryClose()` op instead of `core.close()` then?

This is exactly how it's handled by [the implementation of the `Disposable` interface for `Deno.FsFile`](https://github.com/denoland/deno/blob/v1.44.2/ext/fs/30_fs.js#L801-L803):

```ts
  [SymbolDispose]() {
    core.tryClose(this.#rid);
  }
```

…so declaring the variable `file` using the [`using`](https://github.com/tc39/proposal-explicit-resource-management) keyword (instead of `const`/`let`/`var`) will ensure that the file resource is closed at the end of the scope (whether or not it was closed during stream cleanup). Here's an example based on [the original code example](https://github.com/denoland/deno/issues/15442#issue-1333997586):

`download_logo.ts`:
```ts
async function main() {
  const res = await fetch("https://deno.land/logo.svg");

  const createAndWriteOnlyOptions: Deno.OpenOptions = {
    create: true,
    read: false,
    write: true,
  };

  using file = await Deno.open("deno_logo.svg", createAndWriteOnlyOptions); /*
  ^^^^^
  Explicit resource management enables the file to be closed automatically
  at the end of this scope by the built-in runtime implementation */

  await res.body?.pipeTo(file.writable);
} // At this point, the file is closed if it wasn't already

await main();
```

